üåç Interactive Web Mapping using Python & Folium (Google Colab)
Recently, I explored interactive web mapping using Python‚Äôs Folium library in Google Colab, focusing on building maps with multiple basemaps and vector features.
üîß Tools & Technologies Used
Language: Python
Environment: Google Colab
Libraries: Folium (Leaflet.js wrapper)
Basemap Source: OpenStreetMap
üß≠ Workflow & Process
Installed Folium in Google Colab using pip.
Created a base map centered over India using latitude & longitude.
Added OpenStreetMap as a basemap, which automatically loads and zooms into the selected location.
Implemented multiple basemaps:
Standard OpenStreetMap
Breton OpenStreetMap
 (with LayerControl to switch between them)
Added point features (Markers) for major Indian cities:
-->Delhi
-->Bengaluru
-->Lucknow
-->Indore
-->Jammu & Kashmir
 Each marker was styled with different colors and popups.
Added vector layers:
üî¥ Circle to highlight an area of interest
‚ûñ Polyline to represent a route/connection
üî∫ Polygon to show an area boundary
Used fit_bounds() to automatically zoom the map to all added features.
Exported interactive maps as HTML files, making them easy to share and embed on the web.
üìå Key Learning
Folium makes it easy to convert Python code into interactive Leaflet web maps
Multiple basemaps and layers can be managed efficiently
Ideal for GIS visualization, spatial analysis demos, and web GIS projects
This exercise strengthened my understanding of Python-based GIS visualization and interactive mapping workflows.
üìç Looking forward to exploring more advanced GIS integrations with Python!
